\par 
\par August 4, 1985 (in Princeton)
\par 
\par NL:\tab Now, continuing my interview with Dr. Sonja Samson, of Princeton, this is Nora Levin interviewing on August 4, 1985.  All right, Sonja, if you will continue, please.
\par SS:\tab Okay.  As I recall, and I don't want to repeat myself, I left off at the place wh
ich involved a day in 1944, August 21 or 22 where, involving the butcher of Grenoble.  I don't remember the details of what I said last time.  As I recall, I left off at the place where this man came up the road with a woman.  They were pushing bicycles. 
 They looked disheveled and they knew for some reason--it wasn't clear then how--that the underground headquarters were at that house and also that Blanchard, the local, the captain of the local Underground, that is, the French }{\i\fs24 Arm\'e9e Secr}{
\i\f28\fs24 \'50}{\i\fs24 te}{\fs24 , the Secret Arm
y, had stopped by.  His reason for having come was to simply tell us that it was okay to put up the French flag.  The man approached Blanchard and said that he wanted a permit to cross the lines because, by now, all the lines were overtaken by the French 
U
nderground, that he knew where the Germans had hidden a substantial number of documents and that he could retrieve them and bring them back to the Underground and that they would be of great interest.  Carried away by the enthusiasm of the day, the elatio
n
 that it was all over, that we had won at least in that part of France, Blanchard pulled out a piece of paper and was about to write this man a permit.  I didn't like the man and I didn't like the woman, and I barged in and I said that I had heard from ta
l
king to the man's wife briefly, that down the road there were many bicycles that the Germans had stolen and abandoned, and that I would like to go along with the man to get a bicycle.  Blanchard and the other people who were there thought, of course, I wa
s
 entitled to a bicycle.  I had used this old clunker before and, certainly, the least they could do for me was to let me have a bike.  So I said, "There's no need.  The guys know me.  There's no need for you to write such a permit.  I'll get through.  Don
't write him one."  So he pulled it back in.  And the only reason that the son of a bitch didn't get, you know, a piece of paper that would have let him--a pass, pass is the word.  Okay.  So, I...
\par NL:\tab How did he react?  When you interjected yourself that way?  Must have been furious.
\par SS:\tab Possibly.  He didn't show it; he looked very docile.  If he had expressed any such, he would certainly have aroused suspicion, so he just responded passively and didn't say anything.  So, it was decided that his wife, his so
-called wife, looked also disheveled and tired and I suggested maybe she could stay behind.  I didn't feel like struggling with two of them.
\par NL:\tab Were you at all frightened?
\par SS:\tab No.
\par NL:\tab At the prospect of going off with them?
\par SS:\tab No. No. It wasn't foolish, you know.  It really wasn't.
\par NL:\tab Well, you diverted him obviously from something quite nefarious.
\par SS:\tab Yeah, that was...
\par NL:\tab Very vital.  But, now that you are with him, how did you feel?
\par SS:\tab What was foremost in my mind was not personal safety.  It really 
never was, but really the damage that this man could do.  So we set off on foot.  He and I, and we walked, and I took all kinds of shortcuts to go down the mountain and get over to where the main road was.  I mentioned that before.  That's the major highw
ay between Chamb\'e9ry and Italy.  And it's Valley Is}{\f28\fs24 \'50}{\fs24 re, the major river and we walked and we walked and it was August, and August in Savoie can be and usually is sort of like here, extremely hot.
\par NL:\tab Was he menacing in any way?
\par SS:\tab No. He walked somewhat sto
oped and somewhat frightened.  And it was a very odd experience that he seemed throughout extremely docile.  There were still fire shots that could be heard in the distance and he was frightened and I assured him. [laughter] I kept saying, "Stick with me 
a
nd you'll be all right!" We walked, and we got to the major highway, and the highway was littered to the right, to the left, with hundreds and hundreds of bodies, of dead soldiers, German soldiers.  That was a very strange experience.  I hadn't seen many 
corpses before in my life.  I had seen some, but not many, and it was very odd.  It was very odd, the day before, these were the people pursuing us, these were the people who had frightened me.
\par NL:\tab Did you feel some elation or joy at seeing them?
\par SS:\tab That's
 what I am describing.  I felt relief, that it was over.  I felt pity.  Here were these yesterday, strong healthy men who were savages, because the night before and every night up in the mountains you could sit there in the Alps and as far as the eye coul
d
 see at night, you saw fire.  You know what they did.  They rounded all up the villagers, men, women and children, rounded them up in the center of the village and burned them.  And we found out afterwards that our town was next.  They had, they knew just
 
about with certainty what we were doing.  It was just a matter of one day or two.  So, it was kind of shocking.  I mean, that was yesterday and here it is today.  I have often been awed about the fact that I felt no hatred.  I didn't rejoice.  I felt, I d
on't know, I think partly numb, partly tormented, and...
\par NL:\tab Maybe even disbelieving?  That there could have been such change in one day in your life...
\par SS:\tab That, too, I think.
\par NL:\tab What was the reaction of this man through all of this?
\par SS:\tab I just looked at him and I said to him, "Have you seen enough?" And he said, "Yes." And he was shaking.  I mean, he was shaking like a leaf.  He was terrified.
\par NL:\tab The world had turned upside down for him, too.
\par SS:\tab He was terrified.  And you know, again yo
u could hear occasional shooting in the distance, and I said, "Come on, follow me.  We are going back." And we walked back and we never said a word.  I never asked about papers, documents, nothing.  By then I had figured it out.
\par NL:\tab Now, when you say "back," you meant back...
\par SS:\tab To the house.
\par NL:\tab To the house. Right. He followed?
\par SS:\tab To the house. He followed like a puppy. Now, once we got back, I called Frazie and I made it clear that I wanted to talk to her alone, quick.  I said, "Frazie, something is wr
ong with this guy.  Quick, did you check his bikes, did you check the luggage?"  She said, "No."  I said, "Do it."  We did and, of course, he had all kinds of ammunition and hand grenades and God knows what, all kinds of stuff.
\par NL:\tab Did he have any papers on him which she could check against?
\par SS:\tab I think that she simply called Blanchard and the others and they came and got them.
\par NL:\tab Arrested him?
\par SS:\tab Yes. And three days later, we found out that he was the butcher of Grenoble. You know, Barbie was the butcher of Lyon. This was the butcher of Grenoble. There's more to the story. I'm giving a very abbreviated version.
\par NL:\tab Was he ultimately tried in the French court, or did he also escape? Like Barbie did?
\par SS:\tab I think no. I think that...
\par NL:\tab What was his name, again?
\par SS:\tab I don't know. I don't remember. And when I was back there, I meant to ask the people there. Someday I'll ask.
\par NL:\tab But he was referred to as the "butcher of Grenoble."
\par SS:\tab Right.  Right.  See, what I learned, and as I've mentioned to you, the current work that I do, I work as a forensic psychologist, and I have found that experience repeated over and over and over again.
\par NL:\tab Which experience, Sonja?
\par SS:\tab Yesterday's...
\par NL:\tab Monsters?
\par SS:\tab Nightmares, monsters, sadist, bully, once caught, I mean, they fall apart.  Totally.
\par NL:\tab What are the dynamics involved here?  It's just that when they have power, they have murderous intentions?  Or can be murderous.  Once they lose their power, all their strength goes?
\par SS:\tab No, what takes over is utter self-pity and o
nly one thought: "What's going to happen to me?  What are they going to do to me?" Which is all too frequently mistaken by psychologists, by psychiatrists and by the court, as representing remorse.  And guilt.  It's not.  It's just whining self-pity.  But
 I learned it then, and it's infallible.  Interesting.
\par NL:\tab Now, what then did you do after this experience?  Do you remember?  It's August, '44.  Did you try to reach any possible living connections and contacts?  Or were you so numb that you just wanted to
 stay put for a while?  You were how old, at this point, by the way?
\par SS:\tab I was born January, 1931.  So I was 13.  No, to me the war was not officially over.  The end of the war had not, what is it?  The treaty had not been signed, and I didn't really trust it until--when was it, May?
\par NL:\tab May '45.
\par SS:\tab Yeah, I didn't trust until that time.
\par NL:\tab Did you see any acts of retaliation against any French collaborators in this period?  Late '44.
\par SS:\tab Somehow, I don't know quite why nor how I personally did not.  
But I heard and I read and, you know, the same thing that has been known, which is, you know, the shaving of the women's heads, or women who had collaborated with the Germans.  It was...
\par NL:\tab You may have been isolated from that...
\par SS:\tab Yeah.  But it was also, you asked about the butcher of Lyon, of Grenoble, I mean, and I think that they killed him.
\par NL:\tab The French.
\par SS:\tab Yeah, I think that the most expeditious justice was done on the spot.  I think that, to a large extent, they weren't taking chances and they just killed him.
\par NL:\tab So, you stayed on at the house for a while?
\par SS:\tab And I returned to Chamb\'e9ry to the boarding school.
\par NL:\tab To the boarding school?
\par SS:\tab Right.
\par NL:\tab Were any of your former friends or contacts still alive there?
\par SS:\tab If you recall, there was one girl who had hidden in the school.
\par NL:\tab Right.
\par SS:\tab Who was Jewish.
\par NL:\tab Right.
\par SS:\tab That I knew of.
\par NL:\tab Right.
\par SS:\tab I didn't see her again, no.
\par NL:\tab You don't know what happened to her?
\par SS:\tab I saw her again when I went back to Europe in 1953.  I contacted her.
\par NL:\tab So, she did survive then?
\par SS:\tab Yeah, she did survive, and I think, her father survived or her mother.  One or the other came back.
\par NL:\tab What did you find at the boarding house then?  Were you welcomed back?  
\par SS:\tab At the boarding school?  It just continued like before.
\par NL:\tab Did you feel any special protectiveness or tenderness toward you?
\par SS:\tab I never acknowledged that I was Jewish.
\par NL:\tab Not even after...?
\par SS:\tab It wasn't over.  It wasn't over.
\par NL:\tab It wasn't over for you.  So, you then continued with your classes?
\par SS:\tab Right.
\par NL:\tab Were you able to discipline yourself sufficiently to study again, or was it something of a relief to be able to do that, finally?  Do you remember?
\par SS:\tab I remember that, at that time, I think, toda
y we would call it acting out, but you see, at that time, nothing had really changed.  Food was still unavailable, and nothing had changed.  Except for the fact that there weren't any Germans right there in town, nothing had changed.  There was no sense t
hat the war had ended.  That only happened in May.
\par NL:\tab So, you were still hungry very often, then?
\par SS:\tab Oh, absolutely.  Absolutely.
\par NL:\tab Were you able to get food in some other way, other than through school?  I think, I remember your saying you used to go, what, out to the country, out to the weeds, and forage.
\par SS:\tab Right.
\par NL:\tab Did you have to do that?
\par SS:\tab After that, on extended weekends and vacation I would go back to Frazie.  That\rquote s the lady of the Underground.
\par NL:\tab Ah, yes, at the house.
\par SS:\tab Right, and some
times peasants would give me a piece of bread and so on.  But I did join girls who were, it's called "going over the wall." The boarding school, I described that earlier, was an old convent with huge walls, I guess, about 12 feet tall, that surrounded it 
like a fence.  And some of the girls had boyfriends and stuff that they climbed the wall and met.  I decided to go with them.  I was tired of being so good.
\par NL:\tab Scaled 12 foot walls?
\par SS:\tab Yes.
\par NL:\tab This would have to be at night, I suppose?
\par SS:\tab Oh, yeah.  And on the other side we met boys, and I met up with a boy whose parents owned a vegetable stand.  So, in exchange for a kiss, I got two oranges, which I took back and brought to Paula for her kid, for the boy.
\par NL:\tab Both.  You didn't keep any for yourself?
\par SS:\tab No. No.
\par NL:\tab Were you able to get something for yourself?  You turned everything over...
\par SS:\tab No, but that isn't the end of the story.  Then, somehow, I guess, a neighbor or 
somebody who lived across the street--that's all I did.  I mean I just went out for the walk.  I don't know if I described, but life in that boarding school was quite hideous.  I did mention a bit, I say, I used to daydream being outside?
\par NL:\tab I think so.
\par SS:\tab I did describe that.  Okay.  So that was kind of fulfilling my daydream.  You know, the climbing over the wall and being outside.
\par NL:\tab And did you make some close friends among the students with whom you could daydream?
\par SS:\tab I did it alone.  No.
\par NL:\tab But, I mean, in your own life within this school, were there any friendships that were especially meaningful to you?
\par SS:\tab None.  No. It was all distant.  You know.  None.
\par NL:\tab So, you didn't even have that compensation?
\par SS:\tab No.
\par NL:\tab Who were these other children?  Can you describe them a bit?
\par SS:\tab Yeah, they were--I guess that boarding school would be the equivalent of American high school.  In the villages, say, for example, the village in which I lived, when I was in the Underground with Frazie, the closest school
, grammar school, was five kilometers away.  I had mentioned to you, I think, when I lived in central France, in Vic-Sur-C}{\f28\fs24 \'50}{\fs24 
re, walking approximately five miles to and from school.  Those were the equivalent of our grade schools, but as far as the equivalent of high school, there weren't any except in the major cities.  I guess, the }{\i\fs24 pr\'e9fecture}{\fs24 
 was, which to be roughly translated, if one thinks of each French }{\i\fs24 d\'e9partement}{\fs24 , as equivalent to a state, it would be the capital.  Even though it's not analogous because they are not independent states.  But that's in, say, the }{
\i\fs24 pr\'e9fecture}{\fs24 , that is...
\par NL:\tab Major city.
\par SS:\tab The major city would have a high school.  Now, it was public school and the citizens of Chamb\'e9ry would send their kids to the day school.  The peasants would use the boarding school.  Is that clear?
\par NL:\tab So, it was not private at all?
\par SS:\tab Oh, no, public.  So that all the girls, to answer your question, of course, in France they did not have coeducational education, so all the girls were peasants.  
\par NL:\tab Peasant girls. 
\par SS:\tab Peasant girls, primitive, very superstitious, and all the rest of it.  We were caught.  The other girls had climbed that wall many times.  I did it once.  And we were caught.  We were caught and it became a big affair.  The town newspaper 
had, you know, "Nuns escape from the convent," and it was sort of a scandal.
\par NL:\tab You were punished?
\par SS:\tab Paula was called in, and Paula and the director of the school went through their tap dance of hurt.  "How could you do this to us?" I\rquote d done it to perso
nally to hurt them that kind of stuff. [laughter] "Of all people!  After all we have done for you.  We\rquote ve saved your life." Endless, endless nonsense.
\par NL:\tab Were you able to dismiss it, or were you badly hurt by that?
\par SS:\tab Well, I'll give you an example.  I h
ad kept a diary, and I have never in my life, to the best of my knowledge to this day, have ever been jealous or envious of anyone, ever.  Funny, that way.  But it was a goddamn well written diary.  I wrote well.  And sometimes I am jealous to know that t
hat thing no longer exists.   [unclear]
\par NL:\tab Someone took it or was it just lost?
\par SS:\tab Oh, because when they found out, they raided all my clothes and all my belongings and they found the diary even though I wrote not too explicitly.  But, nevertheless, I pou
red out how I felt about Paula, how I felt about the director and all the rest of it.  It was rather transparent.  So, after everybody had read it, when I got it back I just tore it up.
\par NL:\tab Oh, they did return it?
\par SS:\tab Yes.
\par NL:\tab But it had been despoiled?
\par SS:\tab It had been violated.  And I've much regretted that many times.
\par NL:\tab I can imagine.
\par SS:\tab Because I think it had a kind of vividness and so on.
\par NL:\tab Surely.  So contemporary with the events.
\par SS:\tab Right, right.
\par NL:\tab Adolescent's point of view.
\par SS:\tab Right.
\par NL:\tab How else did they punish you?
\par SS:\tab I was expelled.
\par NL:\tab You were expelled?
\par SS:\tab I was expelled and that meant living with Paula who was hysterical about what I had done.  It was also at that time on the day--well, I needed to have my tonsils removed, because 
I kept getting recurring throat infections, and this was done sitting up in a chair in a physician's office.  He sat there.  I sat here, and the nurse held a big tray and to this day when a dentist has to insert a needle way back I can re-feel it, I get t
his horrible.
\par NL:\tab No anesthesia?
\par SS:\tab No, nothing.  So not only that, but that bastard was elated at the size of my tonsils and insisted that I look at them.  He had never seen them that big.  So after that, I walked home.  And Paula had to take care of me a
nd, of course, our relationship was...
\par NL:\tab Damaged.
\par SS:\tab Very strained, to say the least.
\par NL:\tab You never could recover whatever it was that you had before?
\par SS:\tab I guess, maybe that wasn't...
\par NL:\tab There was not much to recover.
\par SS:\tab Probably.  Thus, I remember the day of the declaration of the end of the war.  I forget what day it was, June?
\par NL:\tab May 8th.
\par SS:\tab May 8. Okay, I'll accept that.  I remember walking through the streets in Chamb\'e9ry and people screaming and yelling and, you know, like the movies that you see about the end of the war.
\par NL:\tab And you?
\par SS:\tab First of all, I couldn't talk because I had my tonsils out.
\par NL:\tab You were still suffering?
\par SS:\tab And, secondly, I was just bewildered.
\par NL:\tab What now?
\par SS:\tab Yeah.  It didn't mean anything.  It was like an intellectual concept.  That was some idea that had no genuine reality for me.
\par NL:\tab Were you thinking at all about your parents?
\par SS:\tab Never stopped.  Never stopped thinking about them.
\par NL:\tab Never stopped.
\par SS:\tab In fact...
\par NL:\tab Did you make inquiries in '44, '45 of anyone?
\par SS:\tab Well, let me just--I wrote the diary basically, the diary basically--I took photos basically, did all kinds of things for my parents to...
\par NL:\tab You took photos?
\par SS:\tab Yes.
\par NL:\tab You had a camera, then?
\par SS:\tab No, but, you know, when people took a picture and you\rquote d get one, you know, school pictures, you know, whatever.
\par NL:\tab And you saved them?
\par SS:\tab I saved them, right.
\par NL:\tab So, they would know what had happened to you?
\par SS:\tab Right, so that when you ask, did I think about my parents, I would say that on one level, I never thought about anything else.  You know, it was like an omnipresent kind of thing.
\par NL:\tab Did you ask about their possible whereabouts?  Any people?  Did you have any access to official agencies, government, municipal?
\par SS:\tab I think that...
\par NL:\tab Did you ask Paula, to--
\par SS:\tab Sure.
\par NL:\tab To intercede for you?
\par SS:\tab To let the organizations know where I was.
\par NL:\tab Which organizations?
\par SS:\tab I don't know.  I don't know.
\par NL:\tab She knew you were Jewish?
\par SS:\tab Paula?  Well, she was Jewish herself.
\par NL:\tab She was Jewish herself?
\par SS:\tab Remember, she was very distantly related to me. Very distantly.
\par NL:\tab So, she presumably contacted Jewish organizations?
\par SS: \tab Right.  One of the surprisingly painful experiences consisted 
of letters.  I think I mentioned to you when I spoke to you before, there was a family by the name of Epstein that we lived with for a time.  Roland, the son, was caught, smuggling children into Switzerland and I told you there was a woman, Latour, I thin
k is her name, who wrote a book on the French Underground.}{\fs24\super 3{\footnote \pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\tx0\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {3}{\fs24 \tab \tab }{\tab   In Latour's book, }{\i The Jewish Resistance in France (1940-1944)}{
, p.161, Roland Epstein and a group he tried to save are described.  According to Latour, all were caught and arrested.  Epstein was deported but returned (p.162).
\par }}}{\fs24 
\par NL:\tab Anny Latour?
\par SS:\tab Right, and she described Roland.  She mentioned him.  So Roland was deported but he was able, apparently, in the camps in Germany to pass for a Frenchman.  And, I think, that he faked being an Arab, which he could.  He had very black...
\par NL:\tab An Arab?
\par SS:\tab Well, to account for his circumcision.
\par NL:\tab How clever!  I've never heard of that.
\par SS:\tab Sure, how do you explain that you are circumcised if you are a man.  He had olive colored skin, you know.
\par NL:\tab So many other Jews did, too.  It's the first time I hear of that.
\par SS:\tab Yes, he was a clever man.
\par NL:\tab And the Germans believed him?
\par SS: \tab Apparently, because they treated him as a Frenchman.  I mean, not as a Jew.  All right.  So, Mrs. Epstein wrote me very moving letter...
\par NL:\tab She wrote this to Paula?
\par SS:\tab To me.
\par NL:\tab To you in care of Paula, or to you?  Your school?
\par SS:\tab Yeah.  "Dear Sonja, Can't tell you how overjoyed we are and excited and jubilant."
\par NL:\tab This is '44?
\par SS:\tab Yeah.  "Roland came back." And almost, a sort of P.S., "I hope you will hear from your parents, too."
\par NL:\tab One letter or did you get more?
\par SS:\tab One letter.
\par NL:\tab One letter.
\par SS:\tab Then I had a...
\par NL:\tab Did you write to them?
\par SS:\tab No. What was there to write?  I heard nothing.  They hadn't come back.
\par NL:\tab You didn't think, perhaps, the Epsteins might have heard something?
\par SS:\tab I was very arrogant and I figured that if my parents were alive, they would find me. 
\par NL:\tab They would find you?
\par SS:\tab I wrote to the places where we had lived together, to tell them that I was alive and if they heard from my parents.  I wrote to the family in America.  I wrote and let it be known to all the people that I felt my parents would contact.
\par 
\par \sect }\sectd \linex0\headery1080\footery1080\sectdefaultcl {\header \pard\plain \qr \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\tx-360\tx0\tx360\tx1080\tx1800\tx2520\tx3240\tx3960\tx4680\tx5400\tx6120\tx6840\tx7560\tx8280\tx8640\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\i\fs24 SONJA SAMSON    [4-2-\chpgn ]    }{
\par }{\fs24 
\par }}\pard\plain \qj \fi576\li0\ri0\sl379\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx0\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\i\fs24 Tape 4, side 2:}{
