\par 
\par NL:\tab This is side two continuing an interview with Dr. Sonja Samson.  
\par NL:\tab About the Jewish agencies.  You heard from none of the Jewish organizations?  No representative ever came to Paula's?
\par SS:\tab No.
\par NL:\tab And inquired about you?
\par SS:\tab No.
\par NL:\tab Were there any local Jewish agencies?
\par SS:\tab No. This was May.  Shortly after that, P
aula and her family and I moved to a suburb of Paris.  They originally had lived in Paris.  And they did not return to Paris, so we lived in the suburb of Paris.  And you asked me, did I write, so I wrote.  I had written to these relatives in the United S
tates.  Remember, I told you about the Post Office which delivered a letter addressed to my cousin in Chicago.  No address.
\par NL:\tab No address.  That was all?
\par SS:\tab Yeah.
\par NL:\tab No further communication.
\par SS:\tab They were wonderful in those years!  They don't think like that anymore.  I wrote a letter to Manfred Hoffman, Chicago, USA, and they got the letter.
\par NL:\tab They got the letter.  You must have been, you must have been so embittered by this total lack of care and concern about you?  Or did you feel already hardened by the world, and not expecting anything more?
\par SS:\tab No, I had never expected anything; I was simply, literally heartbroken from the day that I was separated from my parents and had no expectations of anyone else.  They were good people.
\par NL:\tab And you obviously thought then they might still be alive, or you hoped...?
\par SS:\tab As I learned more and as I got more of these "Dear Sonja" letters, so elated, so excited, \'93Our loved one came back.  P.S. I hope your pa
rents will, too," You know, I don't know, how to say?  I was pleased.  Obviously, people who wrote, wrote about people that I knew, that I liked, cared about.  As I heard more and more about what, about the camps in Germany, increasingly, I, at times, tri
e
d to prepare myself and console myself with the thought that my mother, as I had described, had been ill, and that perhaps she had perished en route and hadn't suffered in the camps.  But until the day that I got on the boat crossing the ocean, coming to 
t
he United States, I must say, I maintained the fantasy that my father had survived.  Maybe, he was freed by Russians, fantasy like that.  But on that day, as the distance between the Old World and the New increased, I think that's when I had to come to gr
ips with reality.
\par NL:\tab What was your life like with Paula in the suburban home outside of Paris?  Did you go back to school?
\par SS:\tab Yeah, I went to the school there, but the most important thing in my life then was that I had a friend, I had a--I am sorry, I di
smissed something because I was so focused when you asked a question, did I have any close friends in the boarding school?  I said, "No." I did have one, but she was a day student.  And she was a close friend, and her name was Fanny.  She was Jewish, she 
was a Polish Jew.  And I think that maybe the reason why did it slip me by, I think that Fanny was far more important to me than I was to her.  She had an extended family with many brothers and sisters and a father and mother.
\par NL:\tab Living in France?
\par SS:\tab Yeah, living in Chamb\'e9ry.
\par NL:\tab I see.  They were in hiding apparently.
\par SS:\tab They commuted between Chamb\'e9ry and Lyon, up and back, up and back.
\par NL:\tab And survived?
\par SS:\tab And survived.  I think, all of them, in fact.  The oldest brother was taken, was deported.  He su
rvived.  He came back.  Another brother was very active, I think.  I'm not sure if he was in the Underground.  I certainly know he was very active as a Zionist and he started--he was one of the people who started }{\i\fs24 Hashomer Hatzair}{\fs24 
 after the war in France.
\par NL:\tab Do you remember his last name?
\par SS:\tab Oh, yes.  Szchulklaper.
\par NL:\tab Szchulklaper.
\par SS:\tab S-Z-C-H-U-L-K-L-A-P-E-R.
\par NL:\tab Your friend, was she identified as a Jewish girl at school?
\par SS:\tab No. No.
\par NL:\tab She, too, had to pass as a non-Jew?
\par SS:\tab Right.
\par NL:\tab And there was no suspicion about her identity, apparently?
\par SS:\tab No, in fact, it was interesting, she had a close friend who was non-Jewish, and they looked very alike.  Fanny was sort of a, the face was sort of high bone structures sort of, 
probably, almost Asiatic origin.  You know, many Jews have this--I suspect that that must have been her origin way back.
\par NL:\tab Did you admit to each other that you were Jewish?
\par SS:\tab Yes.
\par NL:\tab You did?
\par SS:\tab Yes.  And I spent a lot of time with her, but, then, as I said, her family commuted up and back between Chamb\'e9
ry and Lyon, so she was not in the boarding school, in the same school, I mean, but as a day student.  I could talk a lot about that, but let me focus on something else.  Her brother, through Fanny, th
ey went back to Lyon, and when I came to the suburb of Paris, we continued to write and that's how I got involved in }{\i\fs24 Hashomer Hatzair}{\fs24  through her, through her brother.
\par NL:\tab I see.
\par SS:\tab And there were kids my age who survived, I would say that a goodly number
 went into black market, into all kinds of stuff.  "Hustling" is what we call it today.  And I saw clearly that there were two possible choices available.  One was to hustle, which is what Leon did, by the way.  That's how financially so many survived the
 war.  He trafficked in gold and all kinds of stuff.  And the other was to be a Zionist.  That seemed to be my style.
\par NL:\tab Pure and decent, more hopeful.
\par SS:\tab Hopeful.  Constructive.  Building, rather than...
\par NL:\tab Building rather than negotiating.
\par SS:\tab Yeah, and so I became extremely active in }{\i\fs24 Hashomer Hatzair}{\fs24 .
\par NL:\tab In the Paris movement, or...?
\par SS:\tab Paris.  Yes, yes.
\par NL:\tab You traveled to Paris?
\par SS:\tab Yes.
\par NL:\tab To meetings?
\par SS:\tab On weekends, yes.  From the suburbs to Paris the train was, I don't know, I can't remember, but maybe about 45 minutes, half an hour.
\par NL:\tab Encampments, or just meetings?
\par SS:\tab In summer, we had a summer camp, and in winter we had a winter camp.  And in between I went around the Jewish neighborhoods in Paris and recruited little }{\i\fs24 Shomrim}{\fs24 .
\par NL:\tab That must have been a more positive time of your life.
\par SS:\tab Well, the nightmare was when the time came, all my friends, Fanny and then the others, through }{\i\fs24 Hashomer}{\fs24 , were talking after 1945, 1947, made illegal }{\i\fs24 aliyah}{\fs24  [immigration to Palestine], and I was a traitor.
  That was the hardest thing.
\par NL:\tab They had to leave by way of Italy?
\par SS:\tab I don't know.  I came to the United States.
\par NL:\tab You separated yourself from them at that point?
\par SS:\tab Right.  And...
\par NL:\tab Were you pressured into going with them in anyway?
\par SS:\tab No, I wanted to.
\par NL:\tab You wanted to?
\par SS:\tab You asked me what was there, what involvement, what emotional tie.  That was it.  I really wanted to.  That was the only thing that had meaning to me.  But there is a part in me that always has been the old German }{\i\fs24 Vern\'fcnftigkeit}{
\fs24 .  Do you know what }{\i\fs24 Vern\'fcnftigkeit}{\fs24  is?
\par NL:\tab Responsibility?  Duty?  Doing the appropriate thing?
\par SS:\tab Yes.
\par NL:\tab The proper thing.
\par SS:\tab Yes.  It's interesting, you know...
\par NL:\tab Even after all you have been through.
\par SS:\tab In, in German you say to a child "}{\i\fs24 sei vern\'fcnftig}{\fs24 ," which means "be reasonable."
\par NL:\tab Oh.
\par SS:\tab Literally, I think.  But it's right what you said.  In French, you tell a child, "}{\i\fs24 Sois sage}{\fs24 ".  }{\i\fs24 Sage}{\fs24  comes from...
\par NL:\tab Wisdom.
\par SS:\tab }{\i\fs24 Sagesse}{\fs24 .  Wisdom, and in English, it's "be good."
\par NL:\tab Interesting.  You were the only one of the group that decided you just couldn't make that threshold of illegality.
\par SS:\tab No. No. Nothing to do, God forbid.  I had been illegal all these years.  No.
\par NL:\tab I'm stumbling here.
\par SS:\tab No. Okay.  Going to a }{\i\fs24 kibbutz}{\fs24 
, I understood its profound limitations.  Just remember, I had lived all those years on farms in villages; I knew farming inside out.  I also knew that what I really wanted to do was to get an education, become educated.  I knew that in France there was n
o way.  I had no papers.  I couldn't stay in France.  I was not a French citizen.  I was }{\i\fs24 apatride}{\fs24 .
\par NL:\tab Stateless.
\par SS:\tab Stateless, and you know, you can live in France for 582 years and not obtain French citizenship.  But even if I had, with whom and where wo
uld I have stayed.  There was nothing for me in France.  There was no place, there was nothing.  And so I thought, as I said, that was probably, that was undoubtedly the hardest decision of my life, which was that my plan was to come to America because I 
knew, I had read, that in America I could go, I could work and go to school, and my plan was to get a degree and then go to Israel, and I'd be much more useful and valuable to Israel.
\par NL:\tab You were afraid, in other words, that going with the }{\i\fs24 Hashomer Hatzair}{\fs24 
 group you would become involved in building a kibbutz, working on the farm, and thus you would be deprived of schooling?  You didn't think you could get any schooling in Palestine?
\par SS:\tab Right.  And at that time, it was realistic, wasn't it?
\par NL:\tab At that time it was, of course, still very primitive and...
\par SS:\tab It was 1947.
\par NL:\tab Were there any agents coming in from Palestine, from Jewish Palestine, to try to convince you to go, or was the movement itself in a momentum of leaving?  Did you have youth leaders?
\par SS:\tab Oh, yes, }{\i\fs24 shelichim}{\fs24 .
\par NL:\tab }{\i\fs24 Shelichim}{\fs24  did come.
\par SS:\tab Oh, yeah.
\par NL:\tab And they weren't able to prevail on you, obviously?
\par SS:\tab I think, Nora, you don't quite get it.  I didn't talk very much about these things to anybody.  I mean, this was my private, my own struggle.
\par NL:\tab Your evaluation of things.  I see.  I thought once in }{\i\fs24 Hashomer Hatzair}{\fs24  you could begin to share lots of private things.
\par SS:\tab I did share, I did share my doubts and my struggle with Fanny.
\par NL:\tab With Fanny.
\par SS:\tab Yeah.
\par NL:\tab Let's go back a bit because it
 would be interesting, I think, to hear what the movement meant to you while you were active between '45 and '47.  Did it divert you? [clicking in background] So, Sonja, could you speak a little more about some of the activities of the }{\i\fs24 
Hashomer Hatzair}{\fs24  group?
\par SS:\tab Did I say that on tape about the fact that after the war, yes, I think I did, many people went, youth went into hustling and there was nothing for me in France.
\par NL:\tab Right, but once you found }{\i\fs24 Hashomer Hatzair}{\fs24 , after you were in it for two years, very impressionable and important years, what did those experiences give to you?
\par SS:\tab Give me a sense that there is life beyond destruction, that there is something that can be built, that there is something to look forward to, that there are ideals that are b
igger than the individual.  I became an atheist, I think, after I got out of the camp.  If you recall, I had said, I think, had mentioned earlier that my father was a very Orthodox man and felt that he didn't want to hide because he had done no wrong, and
 God knew this.  And I became very literal about it.  If that's what happens, then God is wrong.  There is no God.  The hell with that.  What }{\i\fs24 Hashomer}{\fs24 
 did was give me something that was a kind of faith, an organized system of beliefs.  Even though, as you know }{\i\fs24 Hashomer}{\fs24  is...
\par NL:\tab Left wing.
\par SS:\tab Left wing.
\par NL:\tab Secular.
\par SS:\tab Secular, and it made it possible for me to integrate being a Jew and building.  Does that answer...?
\par NL:\tab Also, I wonder if you could help also to analyze your own feelings of Jewishness. Obviously, you had had to conceal your identity for many years.  Did you not at some time before you joined }{\i\fs24 Hashomer Hatzair}{\fs24 
, feel negatively about being a Jew, since Jews were suffering and you as a Jew were caused to suffer?
\par SS:\tab No.
\par NL:\tab You never did?
\par SS:\tab No.
\par NL:\tab Ah, that's interesting.
\par SS:\tab No. I never denied to myself that I was Jewish.
\par NL:\tab Not so much deny it, but...
\par SS:\tab God, I wish I had been born something else?
\par NL:\tab Yeah.
\par SS:\tab No.
\par NL:\tab Or that you didn't want to face the world as a Jew after all the suffering, nothing like that?
\par SS:\tab No, it never occurred to me.
\par NL:\tab Had you heard much about, or anything about the Zionist movement during the war, any echoes of the struggle to establish a Jewish homeland?
\par SS:\tab No.
\par NL:\tab That is, not until you came to this movement outside Paris?
\par SS:\tab Right.  Right.
\par NL:\tab Do you remember the first encounter you had?
\par SS:\tab No, as I showed you that picture of the first meeting, clandestine in 1943, all I have got is that photo and I have no idea.
\par NL:\tab Where it was.
\par SS:\tab Right.
\par NL:\tab It must have been well outside of Paris?  Just before you moved.
\par SS:\tab I have to look up on the map where it was.
\par NL:\tab And then your friend Fanny was with you in the movement in and outside of Paris?  So, you had meetings and you had encampments and singing and dancing, I suppose?
\par SS:\tab And seminars, and they were extremely important.  It is through }{\i\fs24 Hashomer}{\fs24  that I met another friend that I really liked.  Fanny and her family returned to Lyon, and the
y lived in Lyon.  We only met when we had annual or semi-annual meetings.  The rest of the time, then, I was with the Parisian area }{\i\fs24 Hashomer}{\fs24 
.  I met a friend there, also.  Her name just fell out of my head.  Regina.  Regina was a student.  Regina lived in one of these typical in-the-ghetto dwellings.
\par NL:\tab In Paris?
\par SS:\tab In Paris, which was a barren room, no plaster, just rough stone.  Humid, damp, roof leaking, and so on.
\par NL:\tab She was a Parisian Jew?
\par SS:\tab Yes.
\par NL:\tab She originally came from Eastern Europe?
\par SS:\tab Fr
om Paris.  But she was going to the university.  And she took extensive notes from the lectures, and one of the things that I loved doing in the evening--I often spent weekends with her--I would stay up all night and read her notes on philosophy and loved
 it.
\par NL:\tab From the university?
\par SS:\tab Yes.  Her notes.
\par NL:\tab Marvelous.
\par SS:\tab And loved it.  Regina was older, I was 15 or 16, she was 18, 19.  And that earlier I said, you know, my major reason for coming to the United States was to go to school.  That just 
knocked me out.  That knocked me out, you know.  All these notes.  Well, of course, I didn't know it then.  I understood that much later, but from }{\i\fs24 Hashomer}{\fs24 
 I learned all these wonderful things.  I learned about Marxism, I learned about, you know, different
 theories and ways of putting the world together.  I learned about sexuality.  I learned about Freud, I learned about masturbation, I learned everything.  I mean, it was wonderful. [laughter]
\par NL:\tab A liberal education.  The members were survivor children, for the most part, or did some of them have parents in France at the time?
\par SS:\tab Oh, yeah, it was everybody, you know.
\par NL,\tab A mixture.
\par SS:\tab Yes.
\par NL:\tab And what was the impact of the }{\i\fs24 shlichim}{\fs24  who came, the emissaries from Palestine?  Was that a thrilling encounter for you to hear from someone who was actually on the land?  Or were these French Jews essentially?
\par SS:\tab No, I don't think they were, they--I don't know; some, I think, may have been }{\i\fs24 sabras}{\fs24  [native to then Palestine].  I don't remember.
\par NL:\tab Do you want to speak a little about your feelings about a }{\i\fs24 kibbutz}{\fs24 , whether that attracted you, theoretically?  Could you see yourself as part of it?
\par SS:\tab As I said, theoretically, it attracted me.  Emotionally, it knocked me out.  I mean, I loved it.  The whole idea, of all
 Jews, all people like myself, all my age, we had survived this nightmare.  Again, this looking forward to building.  And, I think, the first time, a sense of superiority.  And I remember wearing...
\par NL:\tab You felt this was a Jewish concept?  Is that what you mean?
\par SS:\tab I don't know.  I mean, it was just so elevating, so exhilarating, that wearing the }{\i\fs24 Hashomer}{\fs24 
 uniform which was basically, you know, those workers' blue shirts.  Maybe that's why I still like blue.  I love blue.  [laughter] I remember, I think in 
today's parlance one would call it "being on a high." And it was a high.  I remember doing dumb things like when I took the Metro in Paris, I remember an old lady }{\i\fs24 shlepping}{\fs24  some bags, or whatever, "Let me help you, }{\i\fs24 madame}{
\fs24 ." You know, taking her bags and helping and doing.  It was that kind of thing.
\par NL:\tab High ethical concepts.  And these people lived by them, it seems.
\par SS:\tab And it was great.  It was very, very exciting.
\par NL:\tab Did you meet with other units of }{\i\fs24 Hashomer Hatzair}{\fs24 ?  Did you have a sense that it was large movement behind you, or...
\par SS:\tab No, as you saw the different--I always say "No" when I mean "Yes."  It's okay.  You saw the photo of the }{\i\fs24 machane}{\fs24  [encampment] in Jura which brought together all }{\i\fs24 shomrim}{\fs24  from all over France.
\par NL:\tab Oh, it was not just the regional conference, it was...
\par SS:\tab How many kids do you think survived?
\par NL:\tab Well, we know that Youth Aliyah took many, many thousands of children from all over Europe to Palestine.
\par SS:\tab We are talking France.
\par NL:\tab France obviously had, of course, there were other youth movements.
\par SS:\tab That's right.
\par NL:\tab So, quantitatively, there were perhaps many more.
\par SS:\tab I'm sorry...
\par NL:\tab Did you have growing reservations about the ultimate decision to go to Palestine?  Or did it, did the decision not to stay with the group com
e rather suddenly, when the other kids had to make the decision to leave illegally?  Do you remember that process?
\par SS:\tab I was fearless, I think you got that. I was not recklessly endangering myself ever during the war or endangering anybody else.
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par SS:\tab You know that's what we talked about earlier.  About not letting Peter or Paul know that I was Jewish or the others know.  I was in the Underground now.  I was never afraid, so going on }{\i\fs24 aliyah}{\fs24 
, you know, didn't bother me.  That wasn't the issue.
\par NL:\tab Excuse me.  Maybe I didn't phrase the question.  You ultimately decided to go to the United States, as you said.
\par SS:\tab For the stated reason.
\par NL:\tab For educational opportunity.
\par SS:\tab Purely, and I was sure that once I obtained my degree, I would go to Israel.
\par NL:\tab You would return, or you would go to Israel.
\par SS:\tab Sure.  Yes.  It was a temporary--in my mind very much...
\par NL:\tab This was a means to an end, going to America.
\par SS:\tab Exactly.  I felt very much that I would be vastly more useful to Israel if I had an education.
\par NL:\tab And did you discuss this intermediate plan with the other folks in the movement?
\par SS:\tab Only with one friend.  I think, probably Regina, maybe two or three friends.
\par NL:\tab And the other point in my question was: Did the group decide to leave for Palestine illegally suddenly, or was this a growing decision-making process?
\par SS:\tab It was a growing.  I think Fanny went to Israel a year later.  We corresponded.  I corresponded regularly with Fanny from, well, always in fact, because she had commuted, first between Lyon and Chamb\'e9
ry and then, when I lived in the suburb of Paris.  I saw her again 1954 in Israel.  It was an anguished reunion.  It was pretty horrible for me.  But up until then...
\par NL:\tab She hadn't forgiven you for not coming, is that...?
\par SS:\tab In part.  The tim
ing was atrocious.  She gave birth to her first child, which was a terrible time.  I went with my husband, who was a snotty American Jew.  They certainly didn't hit it off.  And I was an outsider.  I was American.  I was all the things that they disliked.

\par NL:\tab They had turned their backs on the diaspora.
\par SS:\tab Right, and up until then Fanny and I corresponded very, very regularly and shared our torment.  She was tormented about leaving France, going to Israel and, I think, that probably most people, most, I do
n't know what to call them, kids, we were kids.  It also meant that after having survived the war, it meant turning your back on your parents for them.  It was hard for the parents, it was hard for them, it was hard for everybody.  There were many doubts.
  It was agony.  But, to me, the agony was, of course, of a different order.  I was a traitor and, additionally, I...
\par NL:\tab Did they, in so many words, condemn you?
\par SS:\tab Oh, yeah, oh, yes.
\par NL:\tab Sonja?
\par SS:\tab Yes.
\par NL:\tab The whole group left as a group?
\par SS:\tab No. Fanny, for example, went to Gvulot [alternate spelling: Gevulot] which is in the Negev.  She married a man, a boy, then from Belgium.  They were in various camps, }{\i\fs24 kibbutzim}{\fs24 , you know.
\par NL:\tab But their departure from France...
\par SS:\tab Was not }{\i\fs24 en masse}{\fs24 .
\par 
\par \sect }\sectd \linex0\headery1080\footery1080\sectdefaultcl {\header \pard\plain \qr \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\tx-360\tx0\tx360\tx1080\tx1800\tx2520\tx3240\tx3960\tx4680\tx5400\tx6120\tx6840\tx7560\tx8280\tx8640\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\i\fs24 SONJA SAMSON    [5-1-\chpgn ]    }{
\par }{\fs24 
\par }}\pard\plain \qj \fi576\li0\ri0\sl379\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx0\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\i\fs24 Tape 5, side 1:}{
\fs24 
\par 
\par NL:\tab Tape 5, Side 1, continuing our interview with Dr. Sonja Samson.  
\par NL:\tab So they left in the middle of 1947 and...
\par SS:\tab Uli was the first one that I knew who left.  He was a survivor.  He was the young man who played harmonica so beautifully, and by watching him I taught myself.
\par NL:\tab Really?
\par SS:\tab Yeah.  Uli made a wrong turn when he got off the boat in Haifa and the Arabs assassinated him.  I left France to come to America in April, '47.
\par NL:\tab Excuse me. Sonja.  Can we backtrack a little bit.  You were living all this time with Paula?
\par SS:\tab Right.
\par NL:\tab And going on weekend encampments and so on.
\par SS:\tab No, weekend to Paris mostly, to deal with the young kids, recruiting.
\par NL:\tab Recruiting.
\par SS:\tab And training them.
\par NL:\tab May I ask, was she in effect still supporting you then, or was she getting some help from a Jewish agency?
\par SS:\tab I don't know.
\par NL:\tab To support you.
\par SS:\tab I don't know.  I don't think so.  I really don't think so.  I don't know, Nora.  You know more about that than I, but, I didn't know anybody who got help from the Jewish agency.  Let me tell you, I want to finish about }{\i\fs24 Hashomer Hatzair}{
\fs24 .  I don't like all these loose threads.
\par NL:\tab Yes.
\par SS:\tab One of the things that happened when I came to Israel and talked to the }{\i\fs24 chaverim}{\fs24 
 [buddies, comrades] that was startling to me was--I must say that I went to Israel and France, after having been in the United States in 1953 because I wanted two things before I could go.  Number one, I wanted to have the American citizenship, and 
number two, I wanted to finish college.  So in 1952, I obtained my BA and my citizenship, and then I started working and saving money for the trip.  So I went in 1953.  Very orderly.  Then, I had thought and rethought this whole issue of Marxism.  And I w
as especially appalled by the arguments and by the reasoning and by the thinking and, you know, I had a BA in 1952.
\par NL:\tab This thinking of the }{\i\fs24 Hashomer Hatzair}{\fs24  people and their identification with the Soviet Union?
\par SS:\tab In part, but also the level of argument.
  Biology was not my major, but I knew a lot of biology.  In 1952 we still had an education when we graduated.  And they were, you know, arguing everything, biology, history, genetics, whatever, from the Marxist point of view, and I knew that that was una
cceptable.  I mean, it defied all empirical evidence, etc., etc.  So it was very difficult.  So, it wasn't just what I started about, having a sarcastic, snotty American Jewish boy for a husband but in addition...
\par NL:\tab Your own development.
\par SS:\tab My own development.  I had totally outgrown that kind of thinking.  And I saw what it lead.  For example, on one }{\i\fs24 kibbutz}{\fs24 , we stayed in Gvulot, in the Negev, and they were planting onions.  So I worked in the }{\i\fs24 kibbutz}{
\fs24  and it was the way, the attitude.  It was a fanatic way of planting onions.  People lined up in different rows racing with each other and on and on and...
\par NL:\tab Seemed regimented to you?  And doctrinaire?
\par SS:\tab And fallacious.  I had lived in farms for a good part of my youth and childhood and I knew--and I had 
done hard farm labor, that you develop a rhythm, like, when you work in a factory.  That's how I put myself through college in the United States, by working in factories.  And I was working on piecework, you know, making tools and steel drills and so on a
nd I was making good money, piecework, but you develop a rhythm.  There was no rhythm.  It was all running, competition, and so on and so, that what you said, that attitude permeated and...
\par NL:\tab It was against your grain?
\par SS:\tab Right.  It was a travesty of what I felt farm labor was about and it was harsh on my part, I suppose, to think that way, but...
\par NL:\tab Well, but you had undergone a considerable personal development and it was inevitable.  Also, I imagine their rationalization about what was happening in th
e Soviet Union may have troubled you, too.  They were very defensive about the Soviet Union.
\par SS:\tab It troubled me a lot.  Right.  Right.
\par NL:\tab For a very long time.
\par SS:\tab You see, it was interesting, 1954 was the height of McCarthyism.  When I went on that trip,
 I was looking for a place other than America.  I was turned off by the McCarthyism in the United States, and my husband and I were certain that if we found a place we would stay.
\par NL:\tab He was interested in the possibility of settling in Israel?
\par SS:\tab He was interested in the possibility of resettling anywhere.  And I found myself endlessly defending America.
\par NL:\tab In Israel?
\par SS:\tab In Israel, and I remember, I mean, that's when I first had this sense of democracy in the most profoundest of ways, and I remember endl
essly explaining to them that McCarthy was a senator who was elected in Wisconsin and that it wasn't all America, and that, yes, yes, people like that, if they get enough votes, they can express themselves and some of it, it was wrong, etc.  But I defende
d the principles, the system, and I found that as I traveled through Europe and Israel, increasingly defending America.  That's when I got a real sense of America.  I really love that country.  It was interesting. [machine off and then on]
\par NL:\tab So you were t
hen moving in the direction of coming to America, Sonja, and may I just ask this one other question about your relationship with Paula.  Was it getting harder and harder for you to be with her?  Was she resentful of having to care for you or being respons
ible?  Do you remember any of that?
\par SS:\tab Her husband, Leon, was always extremely decent towards me.  If it hadn't been for Leon, I would not have been able to go to Paris to }{\i\fs24 Hashomer}{\fs24 .  He gave me the money to go.  I mean, it was trainfare and nothing else.
\par NL:\tab Sure.
\par SS:\tab But, yes, Leon was a very decent man to me.  Paula retrieved her relatives.  She had an uncle, her mother's brother, who lived in Belgium, by the name of Kubovitz, and I think, his brother was one of the early Israeli ambassadors.
\par NL:\tab It's Kubovitzky.
\par SS:\tab You're right.
\par NL:\tab A very important Zionist.
\par SS:\tab Yeah.
\par NL:\tab Leon Kubovitzky.  I knew him.
\par SS:\tab Well, that was Paula's uncle.
\par NL:\tab Strange.
\par SS:\tab That's funny.  How you dig up these names out of nowhere!  I haven't thought about that in forty years. [laughter]
\par NL:\tab So she was feeling what, better disposed toward you then?
\par SS:\tab No, she had found her }{\i\fs24 mishpocha}{\fs24  and she would pack up "mine darling", her son, and go for prolonged extended visits and just commute between Belgium and France.
\par NL:\tab So you were taking care of yourself?
\par SS:\tab And Leon.  I mean, I remember, in Montgerou [11 mi. SSE of Paris], which was the name of that suburb, there was, of course, no hot water.  And there was no Kleenex, there were no disposable anything.  And I remember some 
of the horrors of living involved the day that you had to wash handkerchiefs and you had--and I have always had a very hypersensitive gag reflex,  and as I was half gagging and choking washing these handkerchiefs in a bucket with all--I get sick when I th
ink about it, with the mucus and all, and like that.  That reminds me: One of the worst things about living with }{\i\fs24 goyim}{\fs24 
.  This was, I was taking care of Leon myself.  With the handkerchiefs.  I don't know if I mentioned it; if I did, stop me, but living with }{\i\fs24 goyim}{\fs24  in Frazie's house, I remember there was no running water and we had to }{\i\fs24 shlep}{
\fs24  the water, every God blessed drop of it, from the--about half a kilometer uphill.  The source, the well, was way down at the bottom of the mountain.  You carried it one buc
ket in each hand and one strapped to your back, and I got by with that because I was a kid and I wasn't a native, but they, in addition, had one bucket on top of their head.  That's why they walked so straight.  I remember one day Lucie and I went down th
ere and did the laundry, washed the linen, out of this cold water from the well, and then }{\i\fs24 shlepping}{\fs24 
 back up, and I don't know what happened.  I must have said something funny and Lucie started laughing, and she tripped and she fell with the bucket with all 
the linens that had just been washed, and we were almost uphill, and we had to collect all the stuff, go back down and redo it.  Anyway, the...
\par NL:\tab So, you were helping to keep house for Leon then?
\par SS:\tab Yes.  I am going back to Frazie now.
\par NL:\tab I understand.
\par SS:\tab But I want to go back to Frazie because of the }{\i\fs24 goyim}{\fs24 .
\par NL:\tab Oh, excuse me, yes.
\par SS:\tab Okay.  One of the things that, no matter how things were and how horrible and how awful and so on, I could tolerate almost everything.  One thing that I really could not
 stomach, literally, was the fact that in those days, again, there were no disposables, but what did women do for menstrual hygiene?  You had a rag, which was used, and then when the rag was dirty, it was soaked in a bucket of water.  And the same }{
\i\fs24 tepel}{\fs24  [pot] that was used for cooking is where the menstrual rag would soak.  I mean, you would rinse it out a bit, and you know, coming from a kosher household, that was rough.
\par NL:\tab Oh, my!
\par SS:\tab The other thing that was rough was when it was cold in winter, how did you bathe?  Well, there was, you know, Americans who collect these porcelain, what do you call these things?  For washing bowls? [speaking in background]
\par NL:\tab Sink.  Tubs.
\par SS:\tab No, no they are portable.  Porcelain bowls that are portable, that you pour water in.
\par NL:\tab I don't know what the technical name is.
\par SS:\tab You see them in antique stores.
\par NL:\tab Right, basins.
\par SS:\tab Basins, yes.  Right.  Okay.  So water would be heated on the stove which was, of course, a wood-burning stove, and I see nothing romantic about wood-burning stove, it's a pain; it's a }{\i\fs24 shlep}{\fs24 
; it's a misery.  So the warm water would be poured in the basin and Frazie got first turn and she would wash, and then Lucie, her daughter, would w
ash from head to foot in the same water, the same basin and, of course, since I was the low man on the totem pole.  I would be third [laughter].  Remember, I was born and raised in bathtubs with running hot and cold water.  Those things were difficult, ve
ry, very difficult.
\par NL:\tab Aside from the hunger that you felt most of the time.
\par SS:\tab Right.
\par NL:\tab Never having enough to eat.
\par SS:\tab Right.  But that, you know, the French are unbelievably dirty and filthy, even when they have running water.  They are pigs. [laught
er] They invented nail polish to hide their dirty fingernails.  They invented perfume to cover the stench. [laughter]
\par NL:\tab That's unbelievable.  What you had to endure.  And, so, to come back to Paula.
\par SS:\tab To Paula.
\par NL:\tab You were taking care of Leon when she went on these expeditions to Belgium?  You were keeping house for him?
\par SS:\tab Sure.
\par NL:\tab Washing for him, cooking for him?
\par SS:\tab Sure.
\par NL:\tab So, they were indeed not maintaining you.  You were taking care of them in a large sense.
\par SS:\tab Did I ever tell you how I le
arned about--or did I mention that on tape, I don't know, about the British landing?  I'm sorry, the association is menstruation.  During the war, God knows why, you know, expressions come about, and when in America women will use expressions like "the cu
rse," "having the curse," the expression during the war for some dumb reason was "}{\i\fs24 Les Anglais ont debarqu\'e9s}{\fs24 ."  The British landed [laughter], I never forget the day I bumped into Leon in the village, and he said, "Sonnie, Sonnie }{
\i\fs24 les Anglais ont debarqu\'e9s}{\fs24 !" [much laughter].
\par NL:\tab That was hysterical.  Oh, my!  Yes, you want to say a few words about the Jewish...
\par SS:\tab Yes.  It wasn't until, once I made contact with the relatives in America that they sent and arranged for the paperwork for me to come.  I don't kno
w if I mentioned before, but I came on a special shindig for war orphans, on a special thing.  That's how I was able to come in April '47,  among the earliest post-war, I think.  Then the Jewish agencies, I imagine, maybe my relatives in America must have
 contacted them or something, then they became very interested in me.
\par NL:\tab Was this HIAS, do you know?  Well, it's not important.
\par SS:\tab I could look it up and see what I remember going to the office, the main office in Paris.  I remember that they were giving 
to--as I mentioned to you earlier today, 1947 we were still starving in France.  There was no food, none.  And they were also having rations and food that they received from America, and one day I said, "How come...?" Paula said, "Ask 'em, ask 'em for con
d
ensed milk," and stuff like that, and so foolishly I asked, and the woman looked at me and said, "You, you're too fat.  You don't need that."  If you look at the photos of myself, I was exceedingly overweight, but that was from eating garbage, absolute ju
nk.  And so they felt I, food on me was wasted.  That was one response.  The other response was that the only thing that they really did for me, but, again, that was through the relatives in America, was to arrange for me from Paris.  I took a train to G
\'f6te
borg in Sweden to come to the United States, so I was under their auspices with a group of other Jews, immigrants, for that train ride.  But then they wanted to give me socks and all kinds of things a week before I went to America. [laughter] So, by Ameri
ca I could tell them how good they were to me, and I refused it.  I came with one duffel bag, that's all.
\par NL:\tab This was the experience of most of the other children, too, you gather?
\par SS:\tab To the best of my knowledge, yes.
\par NL:\tab Non-existent help?
\par SS:\tab None.  In 
fact, part of it was--I don't know, I got very bitter.  You could see the director of the place and various people who worked there in an out of huge limousines, chauffeur-driven, etc., and it was that dealing with them was excruciatingly humiliating.  It
 
was a putdown.  What they were doing was so transparent.  Hell, I had survived.  You know, I had survived the French Underground and so on.  I could see what these people were doing.  The last week indoctrinating me about what to tell in America about the
 wonders they had done...
\par NL:\tab So, they should seem to be making a good impression.
\par SS:\tab Right.
\par NL:\tab You went on the "Gripsholm", I think.
\par SS:\tab Yes.
\par NL:\tab From Sweden?
\par SS:\tab Yes.
\par NL:\tab Did you know anybody at all on the ship?
\par SS:\tab No.
\par NL:\tab Not a soul. It must have been a shattering trip for you.
\par SS:\tab It was an interesting trip. In G\'f6teborg a crew of merchant marines from Sweden boarded the boat to rejoin their merchant marine boat in New York.  So that was one set of passengers, aside from th
e handful of Jews.  The other set of passengers were American war brides.  And the two met on top of each other.  It was a floating whorehouse.
\par NL:\tab And you were witness to all of this?
\par SS:\tab Oh, God [laughter]
\par NL:\tab Did it upset you very much?
\par SS:\tab Yes, of course.
\par NL:\tab This was the first image you had of the New World, of America?
\par SS:\tab Of what was going to America.  And yes, here were all these war brides, you know, women from all over that American soldiers were going to marry.  They were rejoining their husbands, new husbands.
\par NL:\tab And committing adultery in the process?
\par SS:\tab Unbelievable.  I mean, it was grotesque.
\par NL:\tab Were there any other young people your age?
\par SS:\tab There were some.  There was one girl in particular, as I look on that photo.  It was, I think, I re
member two girls in particular.  It was really appalling because they were standing in line outside of the women's cabins.  I don't know if that what you call them, down below the deck, with the smell of coal.  I loathe boats.  And they were standing in l
ine, and you could see them staggering out red in the face, huffing and puffing, and it was awful.  So...
\par NL:\tab You landed in New York?
\par SS:\tab Excuse me.  See now.  There it was useful to feel part of }{\i\fs24 Hashomer}{\fs24 , part of Zionism, part of a purity, part of a, you know, a sense, "That's decadent, that's }{\i\fs24 goyim}{\fs24 , that's...
\par NL:\tab You mean, this delineation between the Jewish world and the non-Jewish world?
\par SS:\tab Sure.  Sure.
\par NL:\tab That's interesting.  And you were presumably going to meet with your relatives and live with them?  Was that your understanding?
\par SS:\tab Well...
\par NL:\tab Sonja?
\par SS:\tab Um'm--whatever...
\par NL:\tab In New York and Milwaukee?
\par SS:\tab No, in New York I was met by a cousin of Paula's.  She was a Kubovitzky daughter, Simone was her name, and her husband, Charles.  So Simone was from Belgium, but she and Charles had lived in New York since before the war.
\par NL:\tab I see.
\par SS:\tab They were lovely people.  I liked them a lot.
\par NL:\tab They met you?
\par SS:\tab Simone met me at the bo
at.  And you know, I wasn't the only one.  That was true of everybody almost, standing up high on the boat and there all these people on the pier.  I remember, by the way, I described the distance between the Old World and the New, and as the distance inc
reased, that's when, that was my coming to grips with the reality of the death of my parents.  Seeing the Statue of Liberty, it was quite something.  It was real, you could see it.  And I'm not sure what it meant.  
\par NL:\tab Did you have a feeling of resurgence of hope?  Of the future?
\par SS:\tab Yes.  Yes.
\par NL:\tab That you were glad you had come?
\par SS:\tab I wasn't sure about that.  It was exciting.  It was troubling.
\par NL:\tab Any sense of adventuresomeness perhaps?
\par SS:\tab I think I was scared.  I was scared.  I mean...
\par NL:\tab Going into the unknown.
\par SS:\tab Another language.
\par NL:\tab Another language.
\par NL:\tab You hadn't learned any English?
\par SS:\tab No. I knew "yes" and "no."
\par NL:\tab Oh, without a language.
\par SS:\tab And "please."
\par NL:\tab So did the Kubovitzkys then take you to their home?
\par SS:\tab No. This was Simone, the daughter.  Her last name was something else.
\par NL:\tab They greeted you and then, where did...
\par SS:\tab Simone met me at the boat, and I don't know, you know, by shouting up and back names, that's how we identified.  It took some six hours to disembark and it wasn't El
lis Island, but for all practical purposes, it might have been.  You know, I have seen photos of Ellis Island and these big hangars on the pier in New York.  And the processing was slow.  It took a whole day.  And, of course, as usual, first class first, 
e
tc.  I stayed with Simone and Charles and they had a little girl, Jackie.  She was about four years old, she was a lovely child.  She understood, she spoke French, they taught her French.  So she taught me English in the two days and two nights that I spe
nt there.  And they wanted very much to keep me for a week.  But it happened to fall shortly before }{\i\fs24 Pesach}{\fs24 , and there were the long distance phone calls to the relatives.  I absolutely had to be there for }{\i\fs24 Pesach}{\fs24 .
\par NL:\tab Chicago?
\par SS:\tab Chicago, Milwaukee, the world.  And they really wanted to keep me and I liked these people and I felt comfortable and I wanted to stay.  But, we talked and }{\i\fs24 Vern\'fcnftigkeit}{\fs24 
 [good sense, rationality] had the best of all of us.  "You better go," and I went.  Do you want to hear about the ride from New York to...?
\par NL:\tab If you aren't too tired?
\par SS:\tab I get on the train--there were no plane rides in those days.
\par NL:\tab Again, all alone?
\par SS:\tab Yeah, well that I had got used to.  But after hours and hours on the train, I 
remember when people said, "We're coming close to Chicago.  We're coming close to Chicago," and everybody is excited and I look out the window and I broke up and I wept.  I think, that's the first time ever that I cried publicly.  I looked around--I expec
t
ed, you know, I came from Paris, cosmopolitan city, I came from New York.  Well, like all American cities, the outskirts are awful.  I'd never seen anything like that.  And I imagined that that's Chicago [laughter].  So, then, the relatives picked me up a
n
d there were two or three sets of cousins, distant cousins, and we went to Manfred's apartment.  Manfred was a physician, M.D., Dr. Hoffman.  Now I'm saying it like the French.  You are supposed to say it like the German.  And Manfred had his practice in 
his apartment, which was above some store or other on Devon Avenue.
\par NL:\tab I don't know what that means.
\par SS:\tab She knows what is north? [questioning Barbara Lerner] Devon Avenue is a busy street, commercial street, and their living room was the reception room fo
r the patients, and the three of them, Manfred and his wife and their darling Howard, all shared one bedroom, and I slept in the examination room on one of those. [laughter]
\par NL:\tab Was he still a struggling doctor, or were they just very poor?
\par SS:\tab A stingy doctor.  He still, in 1947, had bags of sugar hidden under his bed [laughter].  And coffee.
\par NL:\tab Incredible.
\par SS:\tab Okay.
