\par NL:\tab So you never used a French-English dictionary?
\par SS:\tab I bought my first French-English dictionary after I graduated, after I got my BA.  That was my reward.
\par NL:\tab Interesting.  Did you listen to the radio, too?  Did you learn some English that way?
\par SS:\tab No, I only listened to classical music.
\par NL:\tab Music.
\par SS:\tab They didn't have TV in those days.
\par NL:\tab Of course not.
\par SS:\tab I guess TV would have helped.
\par NL:\tab I know some Russian newcomers, Russian Jewish newcomers, learn English through television.
\par SS:\tab I would imagine so.
\par NL:\tab It's a good device.  Now, Sonja, we can go back now a bit.  Which grandmother is it you want to speak of?  Is it mother's mother?
\par SS:\tab Yeah, my father's mother died before I was born.  I was named after her.  I think that the story about my g
randmother is too lengthy, the hour is late.  It's involved.  I would prefer to meet you again, or I'll make a tape and I'll mail it to you, okay?
\par NL:\tab All right, Sonja.  Now before we end, are there any thoughts you have about leaving some word for young p
eople who will be studying this history, the history of the Holocaust, in future years?  Any warnings or ideas that you would like to share with them?
\par SS:\tab That's a lot in two minutes!
\par NL:\tab No, not two minutes.  You can take a while or do you want to think about that and also...
\par SS:\tab I can start off the top of my head.
